3D Print tutorial

From Digital Design to physical model

Author: Nguyen An (220095)  |  Category: Fabrication, Mechanical  |  Level: 100 - Introductory

Got 3D design ? Before you can print, you need to turn your 3D model into instructions the machine understands. This guide walks you through using PrusaSlicer to prepare your first print.

Prerequisites

  • Install PrusaSlicer Software on your computer.
  • A 3D Model File (STL, STEP, 3MF, or OBJ).

Part 0: Installing PrusaSlicer

Step 1: Download & Install

PrusaSlicer is free, open-source software. To get the best results, you should use the official installer which includes necessary drivers.

  1. Go to the official website: Prusa3d.com/drivers.
  2. Find the section for your OS.
  3. Run the installer.
  4. Finish the installation.

Step 2: The Configuration Wizard

The first time you open PrusaSlicer, a "Configuration Wizard" will appear. This is critical for telling the software which machine you own.

  1. On the Prusa Research page, verify that Original Prusa i3 MK3S & MK3S+ is checked (Standard 0.4mm nozzle).
  2. Click Next until you reach "Filaments". Select the materials you plan to use (often PLA for Fulbright's Makerspace).
  3. Click Finish.
Missed it? If you skipped the wizard, you can reopen it anytime by going to the top menu: Configuration → Configuration Wizard.

Part 1: The Software (Slicing)

Step 3: Importing & Orientation

  1. Open PrusaSlicer.
  2. Drag and Drop your STL/3MF file into the window.
  3. Orient the Model: Ideally, the largest flat surface should be on the bed.
    • Press F (Place on Face) and click a white plane on your model to snap it flat.
    • Press R to rotate manually if needed.

Step 4: Settings & Slicing

Check the Right Panel settings, here are our recommend setting:

  • Printer: Select "Original Prusa i3 MK3S & MK3S+".
  • Filament: "Generic PLA".
  • Print Settings: "0.20mm QUALITY" is the best starting point.
  • Infill: Set to 20%.
  • Supports: Select "None" or "Everywhere" depends on your models.

Click Slice Now in the bottom right corner. Check the preview, then click Export G-code to save it to your SD Card.

Part 2: The Hardware (Printing)

Step 5: Preparing the Print Bed

The most common cause of print failure is a dirty surface. Fingerprints contain grease which prevents plastic from sticking.

  1. Ensure the magnetic steel sheet is on the bed.
  2. Ensure there is nothing on the magnetic stell sheet/
Warning: You mush remove every other printed parts before starting a new print.

Step 6: Insert the SD card, load the file and print.

  1. Insert the SD card with the right direction.
  2. Select Yyour .gcode file → Click the button to start the print.
  3. Wait for the temperature to stabilize and your print will start.
  4. Wait for the first layer to finish then you could leave.
  5. Come back when your print is finish and take it.
Caution: First layer is critical, do not leave until that layer is successfully printed.

Wrapping Up

Congratulations on your first print! Remember to always keep your print sheet clean and store your filament in a dry place when not in use.
